Workshop Overview

  We're here because three things are converging: Routing, Unified Sessions, and MSS. Two big milestones are forcing our hand — Coach on the Home Page and
  Unified Session History. To deliver either of those well, we need answers to four questions we've been dancing around:

  1. Should Coach appear on every product/screen?
  2. Should any Coach module be accessible from any other module?
  3. Should every past session be available from every module?
  4. Should the Primary pane always match the active Coach conversation — and if not, when should it match?

  We're not going to answer these abstractly. We'll answer them by working through real user journeys first, and distilling what we find into principles.

  Two tracks worth naming upfront: Critical Path (what we're actually building) and Future State (what we'd do if platform constraints disappeared). Ideally
  we're thinking about both simultaneously — so when you're working, flag if something is a current constraint vs. a genuine design choice.

Any questions before we get going?

  Section 1 User Journeys

  Shortly we'll get into teams. When you get into your teams, you'll have a persona - one LOS, one manager, one HR admin. In this first exercise you have two tasks: Task 1. Map one or two user flows — real sequences of what that person does in the product. Use the below scenarios to help inform your user flow:
-user navigates to another page on the platform
-user opens an old session from the session history
-user (manager) revisits an incomplete MR page (and Coach auto-opens)
-user navigates back
-user (LoS) lands on home page and asks Coach a general coaching question (ie. not MSS-specific)
-user in one 'Coach context' (eg. MR page, survey report page) asks Coach a question that another Coach is better equipped to answer

Task 2: Decide how Coach should behave UX-wise at each step? Does it persist? Does it change modules? Does a new Coach session start? Don't worry about abstracting out; focus on describing the user flow.


